## Personas

These personas apply across all PFM features. Each has distinct needs, stress levels, and design implications. Every screen design should consider which persona(s) it primarily serves.

---

### Primary Persona: Everyday Money Manager

**Profile:** Adult with regular income, juggling bills, variable expenses, and some savings goals. Uses the app several times a week to check balances and recent transactions.

**Jobs-to-be-done:**
- When I open my banking app, I want to quickly see how much money I can safely spend so that I can make everyday purchase decisions with confidence.
- When I review my accounts, I want to understand what upcoming bills and subscriptions will be taken out so that I can avoid overdrafts and surprises.
- When I look at my spending, I want to see my transactions grouped into meaningful categories so that I can understand where my money is going and adjust if needed.

**Design implications:** Default/happy path. Prioritize quick scanability, balance clarity, and at-a-glance status. Short scroll depth. Information above the fold that answers "where do I stand right now?"

---

### Secondary Persona: Planner and Goal Setter

**Profile:** Motivated to improve financial health, maintains basic budget in spreadsheets or other apps, willing to engage more deeply with financial tools.

**Jobs-to-be-done:**
- When I plan my month, I want to see my typical income and recurring expenses so that I can understand my leftover money for goals and discretionary spending.
- When I evaluate my financial progress, I want to see trends in my spending by category over time so that I can identify areas to cut back or optimize.

**Design implications:** Trend views, spending-over-time data, recurring expense visibility. Willing to scroll and engage with detail. Responds well to progress indicators and historical context.

---

### Secondary Persona: Financially Anxious User

**Profile:** Living paycheck to paycheck or with irregular income, often worried about overdrafts and declined payments, checks balances frequently.

**Jobs-to-be-done:**
- When I am about to make a purchase, I want to know if my upcoming bills and recent card swipes will clear my account so that I can avoid overdrafts and fees.
- When I see a pending or unfamiliar transaction, I want clear information about what it is and how it affects my available funds so that I can feel secure and take action if needed.

**Design implications:** STS accuracy matters most here. Pending transaction clarity is critical. Copy must reduce anxiety, not amplify it. Loss framing must be used carefully — chronic loss framing worsens stress for this segment. Offer placements must never feel predatory in stress states.

